Introduction

Overview

The housing market in today’s day and age is influenced by a variety of factors like location, size of the house, amenities, school district and above all the economic conditions. The project is to predict the price of a house based on some of these factors. We aim to create a model using techniques in R and create a predictive model that can be used to estimate the price.

The data we are going to use is obtained from Kaggle and can be found at the link here (Anna Montoya 2016). We are not considering the economic conditions in this project as one of the factors for the price of the house and keeping it as out of scope for this analysis project.

Tentative Title

As we plan to explore the data and build a predictive model for the pricing of the house we may have different predictor variables that can influence the path we take for the project. Below are some of the titles that the project can have based on our model we create:

  • Modeling the Dynamics of House Prices
  • Understanding the Factors That Drive House Prices
  • Housing Market Analytics: Predicting Property Sale Prices
  • Predicting House Prices: A Regression Analysis
  • Predicting Real Estate Prices: A Comprehensive Regression Study

Dataset

The data set we are using is sourced from a Kaggle competition in the link here (Anna Montoya 2016).

From the competition Acknowledgements

The Ames Housing dataset was compiled by Dean De Cock for use in data science education. It’s an incredible alternative for data scientists looking for a modernized and expanded version of the often cited Boston Housing dataset.

Data files

The dataset is divided into 2 files that include training and test data. The dataset also includes a file that has description of the fields of the dataset.

library(readr)
require(plyr)
require(stringr)
housing_train = read.csv("data/train.csv")
housing_test = read.csv("data/test.csv")
data_desc = read.csv("data/field_descriptions.csv")
test_price = read.csv("data/sample_submission.csv")

# Combine the training and test files and price column for test data
housing_data = rbind(housing_train, merge(housing_test, test_price, by = "Id"))
  • train.csv - Training dataset that contains 1460 observations and 81 variables.
  • test.csv - Test dataset that contains 1459 observations and 80 variables.
  • data_description.csv - Metadata for variables in the file. Originally prepared by Dean De Cock. (Anna Montoya 2016)
  • sample_submission.csv - The file contains the sale price for the test data.

We will use the sale price values from sample_submission.csv to add the missing SalePrice variable in the test data and combine the data frames created from the train and test data. We are going to use a 80-20 split for the model building.

Data Cleaning

To handle this scenario we will update the values for character variables to Other and for numerical variables to 0 so that we can handle them better when building the model.

# Fix the missing values
housing_data[c("LotFrontage"
                , "GarageYrBlt"
                , "MasVnrArea")][is.na(housing_data[c("LotFrontage"
                                                       , "GarageYrBlt"
                                                       , "MasVnrArea")])] = 0

housing_data[names(housing_missing_cols)][is.na(housing_data[names(housing_missing_cols)])] = "Other"

Response for the Model

We are going to use SalePrice as response for the model. As this is a continuous variable we would want to investigate the distribution of the price so that we we can use a linear modeling technique to predict the price. A good initial tool is to check the distribution for a continuous variable is to plot a histogram.

ggplot(housing_data, aes(x = SalePrice)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=30, fill = "coral") +
  labs(title = "Sale Price Distribution", 
       x = "Sale Price", y = "Frequency") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"), panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.border = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), text = element_text(size=8))

Looking at the histogram we can see that the price of the houses is Skewed to the left. A lot of the time doing a log transformation on the response helow with model building. That is we can try doing a couple of transformations of the SalePrice and check if the values follow a normal distribution and hence helping us build a linear model.

library(gridExtra)

test_response_df = data.frame(logPrice = log(housing_data$SalePrice)
                              , sqrtPrice = sqrt(housing_data$SalePrice)
                              , cubertPrice = housing_data$SalePrice^(1/3))

plot1 = ggplot(test_response_df, aes(x = logPrice)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=30, fill = "coral") +
  labs(title = "Sale Price Distribution", 
       x = "logSalePrice", y = "Frequency") +

  labs(title = "Sale Price Distribution",

  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"), panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.border = element_blank(),

plot3 = ggplot(test_response_df, aes(x = cubertPrice)) +

        panel.background = element_blank(), text = element_text(size=8))

grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, plot3, ncol=3)

Response transformation comparision.

Out of the 3, log, square root and cube root transformations, we can see that log transforming the response variable gives us the best result of normal distribution of the response variable SalePrice. We can now confirm that SalePrice should be log transformed in the model so that we can normalize the distribution.

Model Building

Before we can build or model we need to be sure on what features we are going to use. There are 80 variables with mix of continuous and categorical types. Not all variables will be usefull and we can use a process like correlation analysis for numeric variables to drop some of the variables that are highly correlated. We will also look at the categorical variables and drop some variables which do not add value to the model building.

Feature Selection

Numeric variables

As there are many numeric and categorical variables we can are going to use correlation analysis to select features which are highly correlated to sale price and then compare then to other features which can be dropped.

# Find Correlation between numeric variables
plot_correlation(training_data, type = "continuous", ggtheme = gtheme)

Numeric data correlation with SalePrice

Looking at the correlation plot above we can see that there are a number of numeric variables that are highly correlated to the the response SalePrice. The variables also so a great correlation between themselves and we can eliminate variables which are highly correlated before building the model.

library(dplyr)
# Select numerical columns
numerical_cols = subset(training_data, select = -c(SalePrice)) %>% select_if(is.numeric)

cor_matrix = cor(numerical_cols)
# Find the pairs of variables with high correlation
cor_matrix[upper.tri(cor_matrix)] = 0
diag(cor_matrix) = 0

high_cor_pairs = which(cor_matrix > 0.3 & cor_matrix < 1 , arr.ind = TRUE)


selected_variables = c()
for (i in 1:nrow(high_cor_pairs)) {
  row_index = high_cor_pairs[i, 1]
  col_index = high_cor_pairs[i, 2]
  var1 = colnames(cor_matrix)[row_index]
  var2 = colnames(cor_matrix)[col_index]
  correlation_value = cor_matrix[row_index, col_index]
  #print(sprintf("Variables: %s and %s Correlation: %.20f", var1, var2, correlation_value))
  selected_variables = c(selected_variables, var1)
}

Taking a threshold of 0.6 for the highly correlated variables of numeric type we can see that the columns we can select are: X2ndFlrSF, X1stFlrSF, GrLivArea, YearBuilt, YearRemodAdd, MasVnrArea, FullBath, TotRmsAbvGrd, Fireplaces, HalfBath, BedroomAbvGr, OpenPorchSF. We can validate that the variables have a good linear relationship with SalePrice by plotting as scatterplot.

plot_data = training_data[, c("SalePrice", unique(selected_variables))]
plot_scatterplot(plot_data, by = "SalePrice", ggtheme = gtheme)

Looking at the bar plot for categorical variables in housing data above (section) we can see that a lot of categorical variables have issue as wither most ofthe data are in the same category or there a very small sample of the data for a given category.

Statement of Research and Interest

We as a team want to implement the techniques of statistical analysis we learned in this course and implement them in the housing data. With current house prices being all-time high it would be nice if we can build something that helps analyze the current market trend and help predict the value of houses that are in the market.

The project will also help us explore some coding techniques and packages that are available for processes like data exploration, profiling, and manipulation in R. We would like to understand the different tools and techniques we can use in R for model building.

The project holds significant business and research interest as it aims to provide valuable assistance to real estate agencies, homeowners, and property investors in making well-informed decisions. By accurately predicting property prices, stakeholders can set competitive listing prices, understand market value, and identify profitable investment opportunities. Additionally, exploring the relationships between sale prices and property features can offer valuable insights into market trends, guiding strategic planning and risk management.

From a scientific perspective, analyzing the dataset will reveal patterns and correlations that contribute to property price fluctuations over time. This exploration will lead to a better understanding of the factors driving property prices, providing insights into property valuation and market dynamics.

Overall, the project’s goal is to leverage statistical techniques to build a robust predictive model, gain deep insights into the housing market, and deliver essential information to various stakeholders within the real estate industry.
